The '''Bariba people''', self designation ''Baatonu'' (plural ''Baatombu),'' are the principal inhabitants of [[Borgou Department]], [[Benin]], and cofounders of the [[Borgu|Borgu kingdom]] of what is now northeast [[Benin]] and west-central [[Nigeria]]. In Nigeria, they are found spread between western [[Kwara State]] and the Borgu section of [[Niger State]]. There are perhaps a million Bariba, 70% of them in Benin, where they are the fourth largest ethnic group and comprise approximately 1/11 of the population (9.2%).<ref>[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]</ref> The Bariba are concentrated primarily in the north-east of the country, especially around the city of [[Nikki, Benin|Nikki]], which is considered the Bariba capital.<ref name="Benin">{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Stuart|title=Benin|year=2006|pages=21|publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]], The Globe Pequot Press, [[Guilford, Connecticut]]}}</ref> They originally migrated from the area of [[Kwara State]], Nigeria, and were renowned horsemen. One of their noted festivals is the annual [[Gani]] festival of which horseriding is a prominent element of.<ref name="Benin"/>

The Bariba people holds an important place in the history of the country. During the late 19th century, Bariba{{Clarify|date=October 2010}}was known to constitute independent states{{Clarify|date=October 2010}}and dominate with kingdoms{{Clarify|date=October 2010}}in cities like [[Nikki, Benin|Nikki]] and [[Kandi, Benin|Kandi]] in the northeast of the country. In the town of [[Péhunco|Pehunko]] there are approximately 200,000 Bariba people out of 365,000 inhabitants.<ref name="Sargent">{{cite book|author=Sargent, Carolyn Fishel|title= The Cultural Context of Therapeutic Choice|year=1982|publisher= D. Reidel Publishing Company, [[Holland]].}}</ref>{{dubious|date=October 2010}}

[[File:Guerrier bariba de Niki.jpg|thumb|left|Bariba warrior from the state of Nikki, 1900.]]

The Bariba society consists of a higher-ranking official as chief of the town and their subordinates’ chiefs. Social status and titles are inherited in families, but the status of a person may be given by the families’ nature of work.<ref name="Sargent"/> Notable subdivisions of the Bariba include the ruling Wasangari nobles, Baatombu commoners, slaves of varying origin, Dendi merchants, Fulbe herders, and other divisional ethnic groups.

Agriculture is the dominant occupation for the Bariba. They grow [[maize|corn]], [[sorghum]], [[rice]], [[cotton]], [[cassava]] (tapioca), [[Yam (vegetable)|yam]]s, [[bean]]s, [[palm oil]], [[peanut]]s and some poultry and livestock.<ref name="Sargent"/> Religion plays an important role in Bariba tribes and they are primarily [[Islam]]ic. The religion was introduced to Bariba people by Dendi traders who were preaching in the north. However a number of Bariba communities have their own indigenous beliefs.<ref name="Sargent"/>

==Language==
{{Main|Baatonum language}}
The [[Bariba language]] is spoken mostly in [[Borgou]], [[Alibori]] and part of [[Atacora]] in northern Benin. The [[Bariba language]] was once classified as an outlier of the [[Gur languages|Gur family]], but is now agnostically placed as an isolate within the [[Savanna languages]].
It is a [[tone language]] with [[noun class]]es. It has been written since about 1970. Transcription using the Beninese national alphabet requires, in addition to the Latin letters, the following characters from the [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]:

:{{IPAblink|ɔ}} "open o"
:{{IPAblink|ɛ}} "open e"
:the [[nasal vowel]]s {{IPA|[ã ɛ̃ ɔ̃ ĩ ũ]}}.

